post_text: Webb City R7 Schools’ Social Media sites (ie Facebook and Twitter) were developed as forums to help the district circulate relevant, timely information while also sharing inspiring, educational experiences in all buildings. It was never the District’s intention for their social media sites to be used as personal, public platforms for open debates. Therefore, going forward all comments made on the District’s Facebook page will be deleted at the earliest opportunity. We do, however, encourage our community to tag and share our posts or private message us if you have questions. Though we greatly value our community’s opinion, we ask that you contact our Administration Building at 673-6000 if you have comments or concerns regarding this policy.

post_text:
Cardinal Parents:

As of today, we are planning on having in-person school in the fall, with extensive safety precautions. If you are concerned for your child’s safety, you will have the option to enroll your child in Webb City’s online virtual platform. The method of virtual instruction will be different from what was offered this spring on limited notice and will provide full grade-level work and timely feedback. Virtual students will be expected to spend multiple hours working in the program during the school day to meet academic requirements. While we understand there are special circumstances that justify the decision to choose virtual learning, we believe it is best for the academic, social and emotional wellbeing of students to attend school in person.

As we continue to get feedback from our faculty and parents, more detailed information will be provided through the Cardinal Comeback Plan, which will be available within the next few weeks.

While we understand there are special circumstances that justify the decision to choose virtual learning, we believe it is best for the academic, social and emotional wellbeing of students to attend school in person.

June 3 at 6:46 PM ·

On Thursday, June 11th from 4-8:00 pm Seniors can pick up their graduation tickets at the high school. Please park in the south lot and enter through the counselor's office doors.

Due to social distancing mandates, Project Graduation will not take place this year. The Project Graduation Committee has agreed to provide each senior with a senior shirt, DVD, and a monetary gift. These items will also be available from 4:00-8:00 pm on June 11th.

Seniors will be receiving an email today, including information pertaining to graduation. Any early graduate who no longer receives email, will need to contact Mr. Flora at jflora@wcr7.org.

post_text:
What will drop off look like on the first day at Kindercamp?

The first-day drop-off will look different than any other day because we are going to allow a limited flow of parents in the building to drop them off at classroom doors.

Volunteers will be located outside of the building with Kinder Camp teacher lists. You can verify your child's teacher with one of these volunteers.

You will enter the main doors of the school and go to your child's classroom where you drop your child off with his/her teacher. You will then exit the building through the gym doors.

Parking will be available in the parking lot across the street and the parking lot in front of the school. Doors will open at 7:40.

After the first day, we will have designated drive-up places for your child to be picked-up and dropped-off based on your child's teacher's name. More information will be distributed when you drop-off your child on the first day of Kinder Camp

Yesterday, Governor Parson announced that he was extending the state's Phase 1 order. Due to this extension, Webb City High School will not be able to host prom this year. It was our hope that by delaying the date we would be able to provide this opportunity for our students, however, due to social distancing guidelines, this will not be possible.

The high school will still be offering a Senior Walk for those seniors who wish to participate. This event has been scheduled for Saturday, June 13th from 7:00 - 8:00 pm at Cardinal Stadium. Students will be scheduled during specific times to maintain social distancing requirements. Seniors who would like to participate or have additional questions regarding Senior Walk may contact Susan Fodor at sfodor@wcr7.org

Several Webb City Junior High seventh-graders participated this year in the Duke University Talent Identification Program. To be selected to participate, students must have earned high achievement scores. Then the students took the ACT standardized college entrance exam in February.

Six students earned certificates and will be honored at the State Recognition ceremony and/or Grand Recognition ceremony because of their outstanding ACT scores through the Duke Talent Identification Program.

Alyson, Jackson, Tatum, Rachel, Nina, and Shane all eared State Recognition. Rachel earned the Grand Recognition Certificate.

Congratulations to all!

post_text:
The Webb City High School Speech and Debate Team has had an amazing season this year and 8 students qualified for Nationals!

This is a new record for WCSD. The qualifying tournament for Nationals was canceled so this year students were selected by a bidding system based on their achievements this season.

Archer Cole, Lilly Shea, and McKenzie Jones will be representing Webb City in Student Congress with Caden Brite in Program of Oral Interpretation, Henry Anger, and Rees Massoth in Duo Interpretation, and Silas Drake and Evan Garrison in Policy Debate.

We are so proud of how hard this year’s team has worked! Nationals are being held as an online tournament this year in the third week of June.

post_text:
It’s not too late to respond to the 2020 Census!

April 1st was Census Day – but the Census is still ongoing. People who have not yet responded can still do so via the Internet, phone, and mail. Why support #2020Census? The census informs where federal funds go every year for things like schools, healthcare workers, EMTs, and firefighters. Your answers to the #2020Census are safe, secure, and used only to produce statistics.

Please help us spread the message - the #2020Census is taking place and it is important for everyone to respond on Census Awareness Weekend:

May 1st, May 2nd, and May 3rd 2020

Once you have responded, please courage your family, friends, and your social network to complete the census, too. Click the link below to get started!

https://2020census.gov/

Cardinals, here are a few updates regarding Prom and NHS Induction.

Prom: We wanted to let everyone know that we are currently working with the prom venue for a reschedule date in mid-June. Once we have worked out the details, we will communicate the date, along with additional information. Prom tickets will not go on sale until the week prior to the scheduled event, so please be looking for additional communication in the future. Please know that we will continue to follow CDC and government recommendations pertaining to social distancing and gathering requirements throughout this process. Thank you for remaining patient as we continue to navigate this situation.

NHS Induction: Will be rescheduled with a date set in the Fall.

post_text: In an effort to offer hope to our students and community the Webb City School District will join the #bethelight campaign along with many other districts across the nation. Monday, April 13th from 8:00-8:30pm Chuck Barnes Field will be lit in honor of our spring clubs/activities and athletics that have had events/seasons canceled. During the same time (8:00-8:30pm) on Wednesday, April 15th Cardinal Softball Field will be lit in honor of our students and community members, and Friday, April 17th Cardinal Stadium will be lit in honor of our 2020 Senior Graduates from 8:20 to 8:40pm (20:20 military time). We ask that you join us by turning on your outdoor lights during these times to honor our students and amazing community. Please note, to continue doing our part in flattening the curve all district facilities will remain closed. We ask that you do not gather at these sites during the times indicated above. #wearewebbcity

post_text:
In an effort to stay connected to our students and community we want to encourage everyone to take care of themselves while home. Check out our “Cards Self-Care Bingo” for the week of March 30-April 4. Work your way through the card while at home to take breaks and connect with others.

The Rules:
Each day, pick a different letter, C-A-R-D-S, and choose an activity to complete in that column. Thanks to WC CARES, we will have one 1st place, one 2nd place, and one 3rd place winner at the end of the week. The top three winners will receive a gift card to a local business.

To win, you must have one of the following: a diagonal line, vertical line, or a horizontal line. Once you have completed "CARDS Self-Care Bingo", please email a photo of your card and a photo of the activities completed to arobbins@wcr7.org.

**Please indicate in the email if we may use your photos on our district social media pages.**

In an effort to reduce waste, the Food Service Department has created a new Google Form for the district's free Grab-n-Go meal distribution. This form is ONLY for this Thursday, March 26th and Friday, March 27th.

A new form will be posted for the week of March 30th - April 3rd.

Serving times for Grab-n-Go meals are from 11:30am to 12:30pm for any child 18-years-old and younger. Please note that children must be present to receive a meal.

Serving locations are:
Webb City High School - Dome Entrance
Webb City Junior High - Main Entrance
Webb City Middle School - South Entrance
Webster Primary Center - Storm Shelter

Cardinal Community:

Tomorrow morning, superintendents from surrounding districts (Carl Junction, Carthage, Joplin and Webb City) will get together to meet with Jasper County Heath Officials to discuss further their options in regard to COVID-19 and the possibility of school cancellation. Together, our districts employee over 3,200 personnel and educated nearly 20,000 students daily. We believe it is imperative to be a united front while making these decisions. We appreciate your patience and will provide more information tomorrow.

post_text: This is outstanding! Congratulations, Cadets!
shared_text:
Cardinal Battalion - Webb City HS JROTC
March 9 at 1:30 PM ·

What a great weekend to be a Webb City JROTC cadet! The Drill Team really put it all together at this last drill meet of the season. Nine schools competed in six categories with many school entering multiple teams in each category. We had judges from the Army, Navy, and Marine Corps. When the dust settled, Webb City teams had earned the following placements:

Color Guard - 1st & 3rd
Unarmed Platoon - 1st & 3rd
Armed Platoon - 2nd & 3rd
Armed Exhibition - 1st
Unarmed Exhibition - 2nd
Individual Drill - 1st Place Jon Gardner / 2nd Place Adysen Howerton (out of close to 200 cadets)

It was a great way to end the season!

post_text:
On Friday, two Webb City students competed at the regional History Day Contest hosted by MSSU.

MacKenna Kelly, a freshman at WCHS, competed in the senior division with her paper on Lady Jane Grey. Ella Hensley, an 8th grader at the junior high, competed in the junior finals with her paper on Edith Wilson and other important First Ladies. Both students worked many hours outside of class to find primary and secondary sources, read many perspectives, and craft their papers. Once the papers were submitted, the students were interviewed by panels of professors.
